Biodiversity data [!]

Ecological niche models require georeferenced biodiversity occurrence data (e.g.Â species locations, which is the response or dependent variable). Such information are widely available in digital format (e.g., online repositories provide data on species distributions like GBIF).

# always set a working directory
setwd(".")

# all packages needed and functions in external source file
source("sourceFunctions.R")
Plot occurrence data with R [!]

Function plot allows to produce a map of species occurrence records.

Download data with R [!]

GBIF and OBIS contain worldwide occurrence records from observations as well as museum records.

# download GBIF records for a species (genus species)
recordsGBIF <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
nrow(recordsGBIF)
## [1] 1298
colnames(recordsGBIF)
## [1] "Name"      "Locality"  "Lon"       "Lat"       "Depth"     "dateYear" 
## [7] "dateMonth" "dateDay"
head(recordsGBIF[,"dateYear"])
## [1] 2018 2018 2018 2018 2018 2018
hist(recordsGBIF[,"dateYear"],breaks=50,xlab="Year")

# get landmass polygon from package
world <- ne_countries(scale = 'medium')

plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Distribution records from GBIF" )
points(recordsGBIF[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Black")

# download OBIS records for a species (genus species)
recordsOBIS <- getOccurrencesObis("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## Retrieved 242 records of approximately 242 (100%)
nrow(recordsOBIS)
## [1] 242
hist(recordsOBIS[,"dateYear"],breaks=50,xlab="Year")

plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Distribution records from GBIF and OBIS" , ylab="latitude", xlab="longitude")
points(recordsGBIF[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Red")
points(recordsOBIS[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Black")

Merging different sources of biodiversity data [!]

When merging different data sources to obtain a unique dataset, column names must match!

# download GBIF records for a species (genus species)
recordsGBIF <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
colnames(recordsGBIF)
## [1] "Name"      "Locality"  "Lon"       "Lat"       "Depth"     "dateYear" 
## [7] "dateMonth" "dateDay"
recordsOBIS <- getOccurrencesObis("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## Retrieved 242 records of approximately 242 (100%)
colnames(recordsGBIF)
## [1] "Name"      "Locality"  "Lon"       "Lat"       "Depth"     "dateYear" 
## [7] "dateMonth" "dateDay"

Row binding (rbind) data.frames with different column names will retrieve an error.
Columns must be renamed to allow merging distinct datasets.

records <- rbind(recordsGBIF,recordsOBIS,recordsInaturalist)
## Error in match.names(clabs, names(xi)): names do not match previous names
colnames(recordsInaturalist) <- c("Lon","Lat")
records <- rbind(recordsGBIF,recordsOBIS,recordsInaturalist)
nrow(records)
## [1] 1550
plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Combined distribution records")
points(records, pch=20, col="Black")

Georeferencing in R

Georeferencing is the process of assigning real-world coordinates to a locality (point in space, pixel in raster, etc.). Automatic process may bring bias to occurrence records [!].

# get coordinates based on locality name
getCoordinates("Lisboa")
##         Lon      Lat
## 1 -9.138006 38.71306
# download the records for a species
records <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
sum( is.na(records[,"Lon"]) )
## [1] 179
localitiesNoCoord <- records[ which(is.na(records[,"Lon"])), "Locality"]
head(localitiesNoCoord)
## [1] "Pontevedra: RÃ­a de Vigo, Islas CÃ­es, TR3, al norte punta San MartiÃ±o"

## [3] "A CoruÃ±a: Castillo de San Felipe, Ferrol, RÃ­a de Ferrol"             
## [4] "A CoruÃ±a: Castillo de San Felipe, Ferrol, RÃ­a de Ferrol"             
## [5] "Pontevedra: Playa Lago, Bueu, RÃ­a de AldÃ¡n"

Data cleaning in R [!]

Data âcleaningâ is particularly important for data sourced from data warehouses such as GBIF.

Remove NA coordinates
# get data from GBIF
records <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
# remove NA coordinates; Give the proper Longitude and Latitude column names
records <- removeNA(records,"Lon","Lat")
## Removing 179 NA records
sum( is.na( records[,"Lon"] ) )
## [1] 0
Remove duplicate coordinates
# remove duplicate coordinates; Give the proper Longitude and Latitude column names
records <- removeDuplicated(records,"Lon","Lat")
## Removing 585 NA records
plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Clean distribution records")
points(records[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Black")

Remove records outside known distributions
# consider a species that only occurs from Morocco to Ireland and in the Azores 
# use defineRegion() to define the region where the species occur and then selectRecords()

records <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Laminaria ochroleuca")
## 1298 records found
## 0-300-600-900-1200-1298 records downloaded
# use function defineRegion() to choose the region where the species occur.
# draw a polygon of the region of interest, click finish and close the window.
# use function selectRecords() to select the records within the region of interest; Give the proper Longitude and Latitude column names

# defineRegion(records,"Lon","Lat")
# records <- selectRecords(records,"Lon","Lat")

plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Clean distribution records")
points(records[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Black")

# remove records outside known vertical distribution (e.g., species only occur down to 80m depths)
bathymetry <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/BathymetryDepthMean.tif")
depthUse <- extract(bathymetry,records[,c("Lon","Lat")])
head(depthUse)
## [1]  0  0 -3 -5  0 -3
hist(depthUse,breaks=50,na.rm=T)

records <- records[ depthUse > -80 ,]

depthUse <- extract(bathymetry,records[,c("Lon","Lat")])
hist(depthUse,breaks=50,na.rm=T)

Remove records on land
# identify and remove records on land
records <- removeOverLand(records,"Lon","Lat")
## Removing 108 records over Land
plot(world, col="Gray", border="Gray", axes=TRUE, main="Clean distribution records")
points(records[,c("Lon","Lat")], pch=20, col="Black")

nrow(records)
## [1] 108
